<paragraph blockId="31.[160,1156,661,997]" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">
Note: This species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Sharpe, 1892" authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1892" box="[541,867,661,685]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Acraea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sotikensis">
<emphasis box="[541,718,661,685]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">Acraea sotikensis</emphasis>
Sharpe, 1892
</taxonomicName>
. Both have red and yellow forms, but the species are separable on details of the basal patterning of the hindwing underside (
<bibRefCitation author="Pierre and Bernaud" box="[281,555,730,754]" firstAuthor="Pierre" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref25629" refString="Pierre J, Bernaud D. 2007. Acraea cabira, A. sotikensis et especes voisines. Revision et premiers etats. Lambillionea. 107 (1), suppl. 2: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="2007">Pierre and Bernaud 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bernaud and Murphy" box="[566,861,730,754]" firstAuthor="Bernaud" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" pagination="954821504" refId="ref23803" refString="Bernaud D, Murphy R. 2014. Acraeinae of Malawi (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae). Privately published. ISBN 978 2 954821504." type="journal article" year="2014">Bernaud and Murphy 2014</bibRefCitation>
, p. 90). So far we have not found convincing evidence that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1892" box="[507,632,765,789]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Acraea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sotikensis">
<emphasis box="[507,632,765,789]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">A. sotikensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs on the Kilimanjaro massif, but all material of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopffer" authorityYear="1885" box="[234,299,799,823]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Acraea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cabira">
<emphasis box="[234,299,799,823]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">cabira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
phenotype encountered should be checked. To this end we have included 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Acraea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sotikensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">A. sotikensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the key and provided an illustration (SI Figure 29i,j) to help ensure correct identification. Material in OUMNH suggests that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopffer" authorityYear="1885" box="[694,788,869,893]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Acraea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cabira">
<emphasis box="[694,788,869,893]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">A. cabira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sexually dimorphic in size, but not strongly sexually dimorphic in colour pattern (in females, hindwing upperside usually with submarginal pale spots; males without). 
<bibRefCitation author="Van Son" box="[585,745,938,962]" firstAuthor="Van Son" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541" refId="ref26206" refString="Van Son G. 1963. The butterflies of southern Africa. Part III. Nymphalidae: Acraeinae. Transvaal Mus Mem. (14): ix + 130 p., 29 pls." type="book" year="1963">Van Son (1963)</bibRefCitation>
recognised five forms of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[160,295,973,997]" name="South Africa" pageId="31" pageNumber="2541">South Africa</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
